security_audit.summary: Documentation-only skill containing TimescaleDB reference materials. All detected patterns are code examples within markdown documentation files, not executable code. No security risks present.

content.value_statement: Master TimescaleDB development with comprehensive documentation covering hypertables, continuous aggregates, compression, hyperfunctions, and real-time analytics for time-series and event data workloads.
actual_capabilities: Comprehensive TimescaleDB reference documentation including API functions, installation guides, and feature documentation
Hypertables creation, management, and optimization for time-series data
Continuous aggregates implementation with real-time querying and hierarchical structures
Data compression strategies and policies for storage optimization
Hyperfunctions for advanced analytics including statistical aggregates, time-weighted averages, and gapfilling
Time bucket functions for temporal data grouping and analysis
Data retention policies and lifecycle management
Performance tuning guidance for query optimization
Data ingestion patterns from various sources (CSV, Kafka, Telegraf, MySQL)
Complete API reference with code examples and usage patterns
limitations: Documentation-based skill - does not execute database commands or connect to TimescaleDB instances
Covers self-hosted TimescaleDB and Timescale Cloud documentation - actual deployment requires separate infrastructure
Code examples are for reference only and may require adaptation to specific use cases
Does not provide real-time monitoring or database administration capabilities
Performance recommendations are general guidelines and may need tuning for specific workloads

output_examples.input: How do I create a hypertable for IoT sensor data?
output: To create a hypertable for IoT sensor data, first create a standard PostgreSQL table, then convert it using create_hypertable():
This creates a hypertable partitioned by time for efficient time-series queries. See references/hypertables.md for more details on hypertable creation and management.

output_examples.input: What's the best way to compress old data automatically?

best_practices: Use hypertables for all time-series data workloads - they provide automatic partitioning and query optimization
Implement compression policies early to reduce storage costs (typical 90%+ compression ratios)
Design continuous aggregates for frequently queried time-based aggregations instead of computing on the fly
Use appropriate chunk intervals based on data retention and query patterns (default 7 days works for most cases)
Set up data retention policies to automatically drop old data and manage storage growth
Use segmentby columns in compression for frequently filtered dimensions to maintain query performance
Index hypertables carefully - unique indexes require including partition key (time column)
Consider Hypercore (columnar storage) for real-time analytics workloads with large scans
Use time_bucket() function for all time-based grouping operations instead of date_trunc()
Leverage hyperfunctions for advanced analytics - they're optimized for time-series patterns
anti_patterns: Don't create indexes on every column of hypertables - this slows down inserts and wastes storage
Avoid using SELECT * on large hypertables - specify needed columns, especially with compression enabled
Don't disable continuous aggregate real-time mode unless you have specific reasons - it enables querying beyond materialization window
Avoid modifying compressed chunks frequently - decompress first if you need to update or delete data
Don't set chunk intervals too small (< 1 day) unless you have specific high-cardinality requirements
Avoid using regular PostgreSQL materialized views instead of continuous aggregates for time-series data
Don't forget to set appropriate compression segmentby columns - poor choices hurt query performance
Avoid running ALTER TABLE operations on large hypertables during peak hours without testing
Don't rely solely on timestamp for uniqueness - use UUIDv7 or composite keys for distributed systems
Avoid mixing OLTP and OLAP workloads without considering separate hypertables or Hypercore

faq.question: What's the difference between a hypertable and a regular PostgreSQL table?
faq.answer: A hypertable is an abstraction layer over multiple PostgreSQL tables (chunks) that automatically partitions data by time. It provides transparent query optimization, automatic chunk management, and time-series specific features like compression and continuous aggregates while maintaining full SQL compatibility.

faq.question: How much storage can I save with TimescaleDB compression?
faq.answer: Typical compression ratios range from 90-97% depending on data patterns. Time-series data with repeated values and dimensions compress extremely well. The skill includes detailed compression design guidance in references/compression.md to optimize compression for your workload.

faq.question: Can I use TimescaleDB with my existing PostgreSQL application?
faq.answer: Yes, TimescaleDB is a PostgreSQL extension and maintains full SQL compatibility. You can use existing PostgreSQL tools, libraries, and ORMs. Migration typically involves converting tables to hypertables and enabling time-series optimizations.

faq.question: What are continuous aggregates and when should I use them?
faq.answer: Continuous aggregates are materialized views optimized for time-series data that automatically refresh and support real-time queries. Use them for frequently queried aggregations (hourly/daily rollups) to dramatically improve query performance on large datasets.

faq.question: How do I choose the right chunk interval for my hypertable?
faq.answer: The default 7-day interval works for most use cases. Consider your data retention period, query patterns, and insert rate. Smaller intervals (1 day) for high-cardinality data, larger intervals (30 days) for low-volume data. See references/hypertables.md for detailed guidance.

faq.question: Can TimescaleDB handle both transactional and analytical workloads?
faq.answer: Yes, TimescaleDB supports hybrid workloads. Use regular hypertables for transactional time-series workloads, and Hypercore (columnar storage) for analytical workloads requiring fast aggregations and scans on large datasets.

faq.question: What's UUIDv7 and why should I use it for time-series data?
faq.answer: UUIDv7 embeds timestamps in UUIDs, enabling time-based filtering and pagination using just the ID field. It's ideal for distributed systems, provides natural sorting, and eliminates the need for separate created_at columns while maintaining global uniqueness.

faq.question: How does data retention work with continuous aggregates?
faq.answer: You can set independent retention policies for raw data and aggregates. Common pattern: keep raw data for 30 days, hourly aggregates for 1 year, daily aggregates forever. This balances storage costs with analytical capabilities.
